the giant panda yingying the female of the 
pair that made mexicos panda breeding program the most successful 
outside china has died of unknown causes possibly a broken heart 
at age 14 
yingying who died late sunday had been depressed since 
october about three months after pepe her mate died of cancer 
said maria elena hoyo director of the chapultepec zoo 
she said yingying had been ill for several days 
we dont what she died of ms hoyo said the autopsy 
didnt determine the cause but zoo officials hope laboratory tests 
will determine the cause 
she said yingying had until pepes death spent every day with 
the panda china sent as a gift in 1975 when yingying was 11 months 
old 
she didnt want to live without pepe ms hoyo said she 
was very much in love with pepe she didnt want to go out into the 
garden she ate but not as well as she used to 
she wasnt as aggressive as sure of herself before she 
wouldnt let you touch her and recently it didnt matter to her 
giant pandas are an endangered species and only about 18 are in 
captivity outside china the animals generally have a life 
expectancy of about 20 years 
yingying who was nearly 15 gave birth to seven offspring after 
natural mating with pepe four survived yingying accidentally 
rolled onto the first cub eight days after its birth in 1980 
crushing it and one each of two sets of twins died 
tohui the oldest of the four surviving offspring set off panda 
mania when she was born july 21 1981 and is the zoos hope for 
continuing to produce more pandas in december the london zoo sent 
its 16yearold male panda to mexico in hopes the two would mate 
ms hoyo said yingyings body like pepes will be stuffed and 
put on display 
