<TEXT>
president bush has called free choice 
the single most promising idea in education but hed get an 
argument from bob duncan and others involved in the nations most 
comprehensive application of the concept 
i dont know if anyone can say it is off to a good start 
said duncan superintendent of a school district on northern 
minnesotas iron range were very close to being out of 
business 
the problem is that nearly a third of the districts 1000 
students have applied to attend school in neighboring virginia 
minn next year the exodus is possible because of a statewide open 
enrollment program that will give all public school students freedom 
to choose where they attend school 
duncans district stands in contrast to the affluent public 
schools in edina a predominantly white district in suburban 
minneapolis two districts do not take outsiders sartell because 
it is crowded and edina because it voted not to take part in the 
open enrollment program 
critics say the open enrollment program wont reach the poor 
penalizes small towns invites interschool athletic recruiting 
leaves some districts with inappropriate staffing levels and 
provides dissident parents an extortion tool to use on school boards 
others hail the program for promoting excellence 
at a white house workshop on choice in education on jan 10 
former president reagan referred to open enrollment as that 
marvelous program in minnesota that is fostering unprecedented 
competition among public schools to make them more attractive to 
parents and students 
reagan and bush are not the only admirers of the plan which 
encourages free markettype competition among public schools 
peggy hunter enrollment options specialist with the state 
education department said the program will probably weed out 
lackluster schools 
gov rudy perpich said the program makes the state a national 
leader in empowering families to make choices about their childrens 
education 
but not all state officials are convinced 
based on the limited experience weve had in this state its 
ridiculous said state rep bob mceachern chairman of the state 
house education committee 
only 435 of minnesotas 740000 grade school and high school 
students applied for the program this year and applications for next 
year have reached 1300 the program applies to school districts of 
more than 1000 students and will be extended to all school 
districts by the 199091 school year districts now have the option 
of voting not to participate 
its a choice for the rich mceachern insisted thats 
all 
in mountain iron and buhl communities still recovering from the 
collapse of the taconite industry a decade ago parents have been 
divided over which school buildings to close in the aftermath of a 
merger open enrollment has been an escape route from conflict 
duncan said 
the lower enrollment wont cut operating expenses but it will 
reduce state aid by 12 million a third of the districts budget 
he said 
if chaos continues more students will leave and it will be 
lights out duncan said 
duncan also said some poor families wont have access to open 
enrollment because of transportation costs 
in edina where the 6000pupil district is 96 percent white and 
the average price of a home in 1985 was 141000 the school board 
voted to opt out of the program 
we kind of anticipated that this would be viewed as a racially 
motivated decision said edina school superintendent raymond 
smyth who denied elitism played a role in the decision 
he said open enrollment allows students to transfer schools for 
athletic purposes and other reasons he considers trivial 
another drawback is the inevitable erosion of education quality for 
students who remain in schools of declining enrollment he said 
but hunter said edina wants to pick and choose its students 
the law says you cant deny a student because of their race or 
their academic ability or whether theyre a problem student you 
cant select and choose which kids are educated and edina says we 
want to pick and choose she said 
the minnesota parent teacher association has warmly endorsed open 
enrollment partly because parent and student satisfaction with 
their school is absolutely vital to their success said barbara 
zohn president 
but zohn noted that the pta unsuccessfully lobbied for a 
declining enrollment fund that would have sent state money for one 
or two years to schools losing students to give them a chance to 
improve 
duncan joked that the success of schools under open enrollment 
may someday be linked to their marketing ability 
how about come here well give all as or finish four 
years in three 
</TEXT>
