<TEXT>
gov ray mabus has gotten himself into an 
emotional battle by proposing to close the three charity hospitals 
that the nations poorest state operates for its poorest people 
mabus says the poor would be better served if the money that 
funds the hospitals went instead into medicaid and attracted federal 
funds but opponents claim to have more than 100000 petition 
signatures to keep the hospitals open 
mabus who took office a year ago after a reformbased campaign 
says the hospitals are underfunded and represent the lower tier of a 
double standard of health care in mississippi 
we have to work toward the day when where you live and how much 
you make are not the deciding factors in the standard of care you 
get the 40yearold democrat said recently 
but he has been unable to convince some people that the health 
care needs of the poor could be better served by closing matty 
hersee hospital in meridian south mississippi state hospital in 
laurel and kuhn memorial state hospital in vicksburg 
the hospitals set up in 1916 collectively maintain only 199 of 
the states more than 15800 hospital beds on a budget of 68 
million they served 77508 patients in the 1988 fiscal year out of 
a population of about 25 million that includes 8278 who required 
hospitalization and 69230 outpatients 
the buildings are older buildings but they are well kept and 
theyre very clean said peggy sprayberry of the state 
eleemosynary board which oversees charity hospitals 
the governors plan sparked a recent rally at the state capitol 
i dont have no insurance no medicaid and you cant get no 
doctor to wait on you if you dont have no money said georgia mae 
jones one of about 300 people who traveled the 90 miles from laurel 
for the rally 
when you go to the state hospital they take good care of you 
they dont ask you if you got money they just wait on you jones 
said if you go to these other hospitals theyre going to turn 
you out theyre going to say you got to get some money and thats 
something these people aint got 
mabus hastily called a news conference to counter the public 
attention drawn to the rally 
i think that the people marching today and i have the same aims 
and thats quality health care for mississippians mabus said i 
think as governor ive got to make the decision of how we can get 
the most health care for the most people 
mabus has said that putting into medicaid the money that now goes 
for the charity hospitals would attract to the state an additional 
28 million in federal matching dollars he also has proposed other 
medicaid expansions 
mississippi spent 440258967 on medicaid in the 1988 fiscal 
year which ended june 30 1988 of that 346324369 was in 
federal matching funds and 93934598 in state funds 
mabus said his plan would provide medical assistance to far more 
people than are served by the charity hospitals 
by shifting these funds to medicaid we can cover literally 
tens of thousands more mississipians statewide we can do it in a 
more equitable manner he said 
but opponents say they have more than 100000 signatures on 
petitions and most legislators from the areas where the hospitals 
are located have worked against the governors plan 
my question is if you close the charity hospitals how many 
working poor people are going to fall through the cracks asked 
state sen alan heflin whose district includes matty hersee 
but lawmakers who back the goverors proposal agree with him that 
the issue is one of quality health care for the poor 
i think the people of mississippi can be served by the charity 
hospitals it theyre properly funded but theyre not properly 
funded and the legislature has refused to properly fund them for the 
last 10 years said rep ed buelow 
