<TEXT>
conservatives applauded and liberals took a 
waitandsee attitude toward the justice departments recommendation 
of federal appeals court judge kenneth w starr as the new us 
solicitor general 
justice department sources confirmed monday that starr 42 had 
been recommended to president bush to becme the governments chief 
appeals lawyer arguing cases before the supreme court and deciding 
whether to appeal lower court decisions against federal agencies 
white house spokesmen said monday they did not know when bush 
might nominate starr but a justice department source speaking on 
condition of anonymity said i understand its a done deal bush 
hasnt done anything on it but we wouldnt have recommended it 
formally if we didnt think it suited his personnel people 
the nomination would be subject to senate confirmation 
starr born in vernon texas has been on the us circuit court 
of appeals for the district of columbia since oct 11 1983 before 
that he had been a clerk for former chief justice warren e burger 
a partner with the los angeles law firm of gibson dunn amp crutcher 
and counselor to former attorney general william french smith 
he had previously been mentioned as a possible supreme court 
nominee after the 1987 retirement of justice lewis powell 
starr was unavailable for interviews monday his secretary said 
kenneth cribb a top aide in reagans white house and in former 
attorney general edwin meese iiis justice department said monday 
that starr would make an excellent solicitor general 
i found him to be quite compatible with the conservative 
judicial philosophy of the reagan administration in all matters 
said cribb a senior fellow at the conservative heritage foundation 
bruce fein a conservative columnist and attorney who was 
associate deputy attorney general during president reagans first 
term said in a november 1988 column that starr epitomizes the 
reagan judicial legacy 
