<TEXT>
thirtytwo medical employees of the veterans 
administration have been disciplined for accepting money and other 
gratuities from drug companies doing business with the agency 
the va said monday that its department of medicine and surgery 
took the action as a result of a threeyear investigation by the va 
inspector general into dealings between va doctors and other 
employees and five pharmaceutical suppliers 
the actions were for the acceptance of travel expenses speaking 
fees grants or consulting fees and for being absent from work 
without taking vacation to do the outside work the va said 
the probe began after an earlier investigation into dealings by 
another drug company resulted in disciplinary actions against 34 va 
physicians and other employees in 1987 
in response to a freedom of information act request the vas 
office of inspector general said that in the latest actions one 
employee was suspended 29 received admonishments and two received 
reprimands which are more serious than admonishments 
in three other cases no action was taken because the employees 
resigned 
six cases were referred to the justice department which decided 
against prosecution in four of them in most cases citing lack of 
criminal intent the other two cases remain under consideration 
in addition the agency provided counseling to 18 employees and 
issued instructional letters to 473 employees steps that were the 
result of the investigation but are not considered disciplinary 
actions 
the inspector general withheld names of the employees involved 
in a written statement the va said the employees violated 
regulations or policies concerning actual or apparent conflict of 
interest through the improper acceptance of money or other 
gratuities many of the cases involved va doctors or other employees 
attending or speaking at meetings and symposiums sponsored by the 
companies 
assistant inspector general jack h kroll said the investigation 
has not been closed and that actions involving several va employees 
have not been completed 
investigative reports released by the inspector general said that 
in one case a va doctor employed parttime received fees and 
expenses totaling over 175000 from eli lilly amp co and for two 
years had a 10000 a year consulting agreement with lilly 
during that period he served as chairman of a va hospitals 
formulary committee a panel that selects drugs for use by the 
hospital 
in another case a va employee received speeking fees amounting 
to 35050 and expenses of 14018 and was absent from work for 335 
hours the agency said in still another an employee received 
honoraria from two companies on 79 occasions including fees of 
38250 and expenses of 34018 
in addition to lilly companies involved were cibageigy corp 
hoechstroussel pharmaceuticals inc merksharp amp dome and abbott 
laboratories 
the original investigation involved payments by smith kline amp 
french laboratories 
both investigations involved activities in 1981 through november 
1985 
donna st john spokesman for the vas department of medicine and 
surgery said that following the initial investigation the va took 
steps to ensure employees were familiar with regulations and 
policies prohibiting certain dealings with private companies 
the va which in march will become the department of veterans 
affairs operates the nations largest hospital system and has 
194000 employees 
</TEXT>
