<TEXT>
severely depressed patients not only see the 
light but turn from sad to glad while wearing an unusual hat fitted 
with two fluorescent tubes according to researchers who hope to 
help millions with the device 
the invention is a hat that looks like a pith helmet with the two 
tubes placed parallel to the eyebrows it was designed as a 
portable wearable way to treat patients suffering from a severe 
form of winter depression dubbed seasonal affective disorder or sad 
almost everyone i know cant stand february and looks forward 
to spring said dr george brainard a neurologist who along with 
biomedical engineer dan benson developed the hat at thomas jefferson 
university 
but he said the victims of sad have an outright lack of 
energy and an inability to cope 
sad is characterized by withdrawal social isolation depression 
a craving for carbohydrates weight gain a tendency to sleep longer 
and fatigue people with sad generally improve as springtimes 
sunnier days grow closer 
scientists estimate that sad severely afflicts about 10 million 
americans about 25 million experience a milder form of the 
disorder most of the cases occur in the northern states where days 
are shorter 
researchers have found that exposure to bright light or 
phototherapy alters the production of the hormone melatonin and 
relieves the depression 
brainard said researchers believe the therapy works because light 
directed into the eyes stimulates a region of the brain called the 
hypothalamus which controls production of hormones including 
melatonin 
how light works to alter hormone production and relieve 
depression is not known he said 
the two 6inch lights five times as bright as the light in a 
welllit room fit under the brim of the hat which is attached by 
a cord to a battery pack worn on a shoulder strap 
brainard and benson designed the first prototype two years ago 
this month they began testing the hat on six patients with sad and 
hope to treat up to 20 this season 
in 85 percent of sad cases light therapy has caused a 
significant improvement or complete relief of all symptoms said 
brainard 
but most patients cant spend their days outside in bright 
sunshine the light hat enables people to fit the phototherapy into 
their busy lives by wearing the hat at home 
patients wear the hat for about two hours a day usually in the 
morning said dr karen stewart director of jeffersons sad clinic 
a portable device makes it possible for a person to receive 
therapy and still maintain a regular morning routine she said 
patients using conventional phototherapy must spend one to five 
hours daily in front of a fluorescent light box the bulky light box 
weighs about 25 pounds and patients often complain about scheduling 
the therapy around jobs and family 
you cant really carry them on an airplane brainard said 
five of the six patients using the hat have responded to the 
treatment ms stewart said 
one responded so well that even after she was withdrawn after 
a week of wearing the hat she hasnt relapsed into depression in 
three weeks she said 
the patient who didnt respond was physically ill at the time and 
will test the hat again 
other scientists also are working on similar projects 
dr thomas wehr of the national institute of mental health in 
rockville md said he and his collegues designed several 
prototypes of a light visor two years ago and found it extremely 
effective in treating sad 
we had trouble getting the devices back he said 
wehr said he was aware of at least one or two other groups 
working on similar devices and his group is continuing development 
of a lighter version 
both groups have applied for patents 
the knowledge gained through the clinical testing of the light 
hat will further brainards research for the national aeronautics 
and space administration on artificially lit environments such as 
the space shuttle 
brainard said that as humans and animals spend increasingly 
longer time in space researchers are concerned about how the body 
can react adversely to artificial light 
his research is financed in part by the space agency to design 
and develop lighting systems for the shuttle and the planned space 
station 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0029 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal judge is being asked to block the 
first application of genetic engineering using an animal virus gene 
in the experimental treatment of human cancer 
the request is contained in a us district court lawsuit filed 
monday by the foundation on economic trends and its president 
jeremy rifkin 
it asks for an injunction to block plans by researchers at the 
national institute of health to use a rat virus to manipulate a gene 
in an experimental treatment of melanoma a virulent and often fatal 
skin cancer 
the suit claims that the institutes recombinant dna advisory 
committee which reviews human genetic engineering experiments 
approved the cancer therapy without conducting proper public 
hearings 
as the suit was being filed in downtown washington on monday 
rifkin and others in the foundation met with the 25member committee 
at the institutes offices in maryland for a heated discussion of 
rifkins proposal that the nih be required to form a citizens 
committee to evaluate dangers involved in human genetic engineering 
members of the institutes advisory group voted 230 with two 
members abstaining against forming the citizens committee rifkin 
vowed to come back again and again and again with his proposal 
the lawsuit asks the court to block the first formal attempt ever 
to insert a foreign gene into human beings 
the suit targets research approved earlier this month to treat 
melanoma patients with a type of white blood cell called a tumor 
infiltrating lymphocyte til that has been genetically altered 
til cells are developed by the body in small numbers to fight the 
growth of melanoma tumors 
three nih researchers steven a rosenberg r michael blaese and 
w french anderson showed in earlier work that til cells can be 
used to battle cancer by taking them from a patients tumor growing 
them in large numbers in the laboratory and then reinserting them 
into the patient in results published in december the technique 
was at least partially successful in 12 of 20 patients 
to understand why til therapy works for some but not others the 
scientists want to trace the white blood cells after they are 
returned to the patient in order to do this the researchers want 
to mark the cells with a bacterial gene that produces a resistance 
to neomycin an antibiotic in this way cells from the patients 
tumors or blood stream could be identified and movement of the cells 
into the tumors could be monitored 
but in order to get the gene of the bacteria into the white blood 
cells the scientists proposed to use a rat leukemia retrovirus it 
was the use of this virus that triggered the lawsuit 
the study proposed that the experimental therapy be used on 10 
melanoma patients with a life expectancy of just 90 days and that 
it not be used on other patients until the technique is reevaluated 
the research proposal underwent seven months of reviews 
including hearings by nih committees the food and drug 
administration and a congressional committee on jan 18 james b 
wyngaarden director of the nih gave final approval 
in their lawsuit rifkin and the foundation on economic trends 
say the approval was not proper because a subcommittee review of the 
proposal was not conducted with public notice and public 
participation and that final approval by the full committee was by 
a mailed ballot instead of in a public hearing 
a court clerk said the case has been assigned to the court of 
us district judge john g penn no hearing had been scheduled 
monday but the clerk said it would probably be sometime this week 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890131-0030 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bush isnt talking yet about his plan 
to restructure the savings and loan system but the report of a 
study group he headed as vice president may preview his approach 
if the 1984 recommendations of the task group on regulation of 
financial services are any indication bush will take a cautious 
approach rather than advocate a wholesale restructuring of the 
industry 
the 1984 report recommended maintaining a separate system for 
sampls at least in the near term but allowing sampls to become banks 
as their activities and services grew more banklike 
and rather than calling for a return to old restrictions the 
group emphasized a system of incentives including riskbased 
insurance premiums and higher capital levels to encourage sampls to 
operate safely 
bushs staff director for the task group washington attorney 
richard breeden joined the white house staff last week and is 
expected to play the key role in shaping the administrations sampl 
plan 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said monday that the 
president hopes to outline the plan in a feb 9 speech although he 
may not have all the details by then 
much has changed since bush signed the task group report but 
although the magnitude of sampl insolvencies had not yet come to 
light the study recognized what since has been identified as a key 
contributor to the problem permissive laws in some states that 
allowed sampls to stray into risky areas far removed from their 
traditional business of making home mortgage loans 
rather than force sampls to revert to their traditional form the 
bush group recommended riskrelated insurance premiums requiring 
institutions entering new areas to pay more into the government 
insurance fund than conservatively run sampls currently all sampls pay 
the same premium 
higher levels of capital also would discourage excessive risks 
it said the owner of an sampl with low capital levels has little to 
lose and much to gain from taking a big risk while the taxpayers 
who are the ultimate backers of insured deposits have much to lose 
and nothing to gain 
the task force recommended that sampl capital levels be brought up 
to the stricter standards applied to commercial banks that is now 
being done but wont be in full force until 1991 
contrary to the current thinking of most analysts bushs group 
advocated that federal regulators turn over some of their authority 
to the states but only to states whose regulatory systems met 
federal requirements 
that would create an incentive for states to develop stronger 
regulatory programs it argued as a guard against states whose 
standards slip it said federal insurers should be permitted to 
revoke the insurance of stateregulated institutions 
currently there are two schools of thought regarding the future 
of the sampl industry one advocated by the chief industry lobby 
group the us league of savings institutions contends that 
thrifts should remain distinct from commercial banks but that they 
ought to stick primarily to mortgage lending 
the other school says theres no longer a need for a separate 
industry it notes that commercial banks and mortgage firms owned by 
nonfinancial companies such as sears roebuck amp co have entered 
home mortgages in a big way thanks to governmentchartered agencies 
which buy mortgages and repackage them into securities for sale to 
investors 
the bush task force steered a middle course it recommended 
retaining the federal home loan bank system for thrifts and keeping 
three separate insurance funds for banks thrifts and credit unions 
but it offered a mechanism for the financial system to evolve 
thrifts that stuck primarily to mortgage lending would remain part 
of a separate system at a certain point sampls that entered enough 
new areas becoming more like banks would have to join the bank 
regulatory system with its stricter regulation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

