<DOCNO> AP890131-0039 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a new drug therapy can extend the lives of men 
with advanced prostate cancer by nearly 25 percent according to a 
study on which the food and drug administration based its approval 
of the new treatment 
the fda on monday approved the new hormoneblocking drug 
flutamide for use in combination with another drug that affects 
hormone production in patients whose prostate cancers are in the 
most advanced stage 
the drug will be marketed under the trade name eulexin by the 
scheringplough corp of madison nj 
fda commissioner frank e young cautioned that flutamide is not 
a cure but he said a national cancer institute study 
demonstrated how it can be used to extend the lives of some men 
young also stressed that when detected in the early stages 
prostate cancer can be treated successfully 
these prostate cancers generally need not get to this stage 
if every man over 40 would have a simple rectal exam each year 
young said 
cancer of the prostate a walnutsize gland at the base of the 
male bladder is the third leading cause of cancer deaths among 
american men it kills more than 25000 men annually and about 
100000 new cases are reported each year the fda said 
the disease often develops with no noticeable symptoms warning 
signs can include difficulty in urinating frequent urination and 
presence of blood or pus in the urine or semen these are the same 
symptoms that mark prostate infections and a benign enlargement of 
the prostate that is common in older men 
in its early stages the disease can be treated successfully by 
removing all or part of the prostate or by radiation but if the 
cancer spreads to other tissue and organs chances of successful 
treatment diminish considerably 
the nci study involving 617 men with advanced prostate cancer 
showed that flutamide in combination with the previously approved 
drug leuprolide extended survival by nearly 25 percent patients 
receiving the two drugs survived an average 349 months seven 
months longer than the group that received leuprolide alone the fda 
said 
the drug has been in clinical development for 15 years and is 
marketed in 34 countries scheringplough said 
the drug works by blocking the spread of cancer cells in the 
prostate as well as in surrounding tissue 
scientists believe the male hormone testosterone stimulates 
proliferation of cancer cells by a diseased prostate leuprolide 
stops production of the hormone by the testes and flutamide is 
believed to inhibit the hormones action on cancer cells by blocking 
the receptor sites that testosterone uses in the cells the fda said 
side effects of the combined therapy included hot flashes in 61 
percent of the patients loss of libido in 36 percent impotence in 
33 percent diarrhea in 14 percent and nausea and vomiting in 12 
percent the agency said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

