speaker jim wright today was conducting a rare 
hurryup survey of house members that leaves open the possibility of 
a public vote on the 50 percent congressional pay raise scheduled to 
take effect next week 
wright asked if he would schedule a vote should members demand 
one in the survey said if the members want it yes of course 
but house majority whip tony coelho dcalif said i dont 
think there will be a vote he predicted that in return for the 
raise becoming law on feb 8 the house will approve a day later a 
package of outsideincome and campaignfinance restrictions applying 
to members 
in the survey sent to house members late monday the speaker said 
he wanted to be faithful to the wishes of lawmakers and asked 
whether they demanded a vote before feb 8 
an associated press survey of the 100 senators meantime found 
that 88 plan to vote against the pay raise and six for it with the 
other six either undecided or unwilling to disclose their position 
wright awaited the replies of his colleagues as the senate 
governmental affairs committee began two days of hearings on the 
issue that has dominated the early days of the congressional session 
lloyd cutler the chairman of a federal pay commission that 
recommended the increase defended the proposed 45000 raise before 
the panel but said lawmakers should retain a similar increase for 
judges and federal bureaucrats if they dont accept it for themelves 
wright has acted in other ways to blunt the impact of the 
proposal to raise congressional pay from 89500 to 135000 
negotiators for the speaker and the republican leadership have 
tentatively agreed to major elements of a package to severely 
restrict outside income 
wright said he would keep the anwers confidential but asked 
members tell me how you really feel 
in addition to asking about a vote wright asked if members 
thought the raises proposed by former president reagan were fair 
would cut the 50 percent proposal to 30 percent thus offsetting 
what house members can keep in speech honoraria would support a 
strict ban on all honoraria and would vote against rescinding the 
raise if it meant a loss of income assuming an honoraria ban passes 
most of the six senators who told the ap they planned to vote for 
the raise said they will do so only if honoraria are banned in 
return 
it was unclear how many of the possible yes votes in the 
survey were firm since the language of the pay rejection resolution 
was still under discussion more than a quarter of the senate has 
sponsored legislation that would roll back the increase if it 
becomes law on feb 8 as expected 
senate leaders also are negotiating whether to restrict outside 
income beyond a simple ban on honoraria the catchall term covering 
speaking fees appearances and articles 
house negotiators representing the leadership in both parties 
have tentatively worked out restrictions that range far beyond an 
