<TEXT>
a food and drug administration panel said 
tuesday that children with healthy teeth may need dental xrays no 
more than once every year or two and dentally healthy adults once 
every two or three years 
the panels guidelines reported in the current issue of the 
journal of the american dental association were prompted by concern 
among some experts about the frequency of dental xrays both 
overuse and underuse 
although the radiation risk from a dental xray is extremely 
low our goal is to eliminate any unneeded radiation exposure fda 
commissioner frank e young said in an news release on the 
guidelines tuesday 
until these guidelines were developed there were few concrete 
criteria a dentist could use in deciding when xrays were needed 
he said 
young also stressed the flexibility of the guidelines saying 
these are not hard and fast rules in deciding whether an xray is 
needed the dentist must use clinical judgment in evaluating the 
patients needs 
the guidelines say children and adults generally do not need 
xrays each time they see a dentist if they are not at high risk and 
show no signs of dental disease highrisk patients include those 
with enamel defects poor dental hygiene or inadequate exposure to 
fluoride or those who come from families with poor dental health 
the guidelines say that children visiting a dentist for the first 
time will need xrays 
most children who have not developed cavities and do not show any 
other symptoms of dental disease will need xrays generally once 
every year or two according to the guidelines xrays also are 
sometimes needed to check on the proper growth and development of 
permanent molars 
the panels guidelines are supported by the american dental 
association the academy of general dentistry the american academy 
of dental radiology the american academy of oral medicine the 
american academy of pediatric dentistry and the american academy of 
periodontology the fda said 
