<TEXT>
john f kennedy international airport has become 
the first airport in the country to install traffic lights on its 
runways and taxiways to reduce chances of a ground collision 
officials said tuesday the experimental system is working well 
the red lightgreen light system initiated jan 15 is intended to 
backstop the air traffic controllers who direct the movement of 
about 500 airplanes a day on the airports nine miles of runways and 
28 miles of taxiways 
so far the feedback has all been positive said jack gartner 
manager of aeronautical services for the port authority at jfk 
they pilots are apparently pleased to see this as a supplement 
to the verbal commands when they cross the runways 
similar systems are functioning at londons heathrow and 
frankfurts main airports and have been recommended by the 
international civil aviation organization to guide airplanes and 
ground equipment in bad weather 
the 600000 cost of the system was shared by the federal 
aviation administration and the port authority of new york and new 
jersey which operates the airport 
the system is being tested at 15 of the most critical 
intersections where taxiways cross runways in all there are about 
75 places where taxiways cross runways gartner said 
the need for such a system has been underscored by the increasing 
number of ground collisions at airports around the world the worst 
such collision occurred in 1977 at tenerife on the canary islands 
and killed 583 people 
the traffic lights are radio controlled from the tower said faa 
spokesman duncan pardue 
in the tower a person called the local controller instructs all 
aircraft on the ground with the new system a second controller 
monitors conversations between the local controller and the pilots 
and operates the red and green lights accordingly 
it will remove a chance for error where the pilot and the 
controller do not understand each other or dont communicate for 
some reason or where the pilot hears clearance for a plane that he 
think is his but isnt pardue said 
voice control will still govern however if the light is red 
the pilot has to ask about it pardue said 
he said it was too early to say whether the faa would eventually 
mandate such systems as busy airports 
</TEXT>
