<TEXT>
if orson welles were alive today he would likely 
be fuming about goats and monkeys 
thats how the celebrated filmmaker of citizen kane often 
referred to hollywood studio executives who tampered with his 
movies it was a line from shakespeares othello and welles was 
indeed a classicist and a genius 
but despite his artistry and the acclaim he received after his 
brilliant work on 1941s citizen kane considered by many to be 
the greatest movie ever made he was never able to direct another 
hollywood film without major interference from the front office 
welles who died in 1985 often boasted that it was the only film 
that was never taken away from him 
but even citizen kane is no longer immune to tampering 
turner entertainment co which infuriated filmmakers and movie 
buffs by colorizing casablanca and its a wonderful life 
among others has announced plans to give welles classic the same 
treatment television entrepreneur ted turner acquired the rights to 
the movie in 1985 when he bought mgmua entertainment corp with its 
massive film library for 15 billion 
directors including woody allen the late john huston and billy 
wilder and such actors as jimmy stewart took their fight against 
colorization to congress pushing for legislation to create a 
national film commission with powers over the colorenhancement 
computerized process they have long argued that the process often 
destroys the original work of art changing mood and intent 
turner has long argued that hes merely protecting his investment 
by tapping into a new audience for old movies of the 1930s and 40s 
young people who grew up on color tv 
i like things in color we see in color turner said im 
colorizing casablanca just for controversys sake once people 
start watching the colored version they wont bother with the 
original 
however while turner presents his color versions on his two 
cabletv networks other commercial networks continue to show the 
blackandwhite originals and attract large audiences 
and colorized films have had only moderate success in video 
sales according to van stevenson of erols inc the nations 
largest independent video chain 
sales figures for 1988 show that the colorized version of its 
a wonderful life by far the biggest seller sold 2000 units at 
the retail price of 895 for the blackandwhite version 10705 
sales retailing at 495 were reported few colorized films are 
available for rentals 
theres a market for both stevenson acknowledged i think 
you have to keep in mind whats out there most of the young people 
grew up in a colored world while film buffs and afficionados want 
the originals 
while two companies are coloring test scenes of citizen kane 
to see if the process is even feasible on the movie critics 
continue to fume 
its nothing short of criminal theyre tampering with a 
masterpiece said director robert wise who helped edit citizen 
kane 
if he welles were alive today he would be at somebodys 
throat he would be bombasting all over the place 
while citizen kane made headlines at first when a brash 
young welles parodied the life of newspaper magnate william randolph 
hearst it is an unchallenged magnificent work of art and 
technology because of its innovative use of lighting camera and 
sound 
while many movies had been made in color by 1941 notably gone 
with the wind the wizard of oz and a star is born welles 
considered blackandwhite essential to setting the proper mood for 
his film 
orson always said a blackandwhite film abstracts reality 
recalled barbara leaming who collaborated with welles on his 
autobiography the words he always used for kane were 
hallucinatory and dreamlike he said it created a mood several 
steps removed from the real world 
for orson blackandwhite was one the things that gave 
citizen kane the possibility of being an art film he said all of 
the elements were conceived in the same way if you change one 
element all of the other elements are going to look wrong 
although welles had never made a feature film before signing a 
contract with rko in 1939 he was already famous in 1938 his 
notorious war of the worlds radio broadcast convinced thousands 
of people that martians had landed in new jersey his innovative 
stage productions with the mercury theatre and his work with 
harlems negro theatre including an allblack presentation of 
macbeth made him the talk of broadway 
he considered several sources for his first film he had 
originally attempted an adaptation of joseph conrads short novel 
the heart of darkness later a source for frances coppolas 
apocalypse now but the start of world war ii in 1939 
endangered the films success in europe a market considered vital 
by rko 
he also looked into making a comedy starring carole lombard or 
lucille ball and a mexican melodrama based on a novel by arthur 
caldermarshall but then came up with on another idea based on 
conversations with his friend ashton stevens a drama critic for 
the hearstowned chicago american 
stevens had intrigued welles with his depictions of hearst whose 
parties at his san simeon castle and extramarital affair with the 
actress marion davies were the talk of hollywood 
welles and herman mankiewicz put together a script that 
chronicled the life of a newspaper tycoon and wouldbe politician 
charles foster kane who dies a lonely man after his attempts to 
make an opera singer out of his wife susan alexander destroy his 
personal and professional life they won the academy award for best 
screenplay 
the films plot centered on a reporters efforts to determine the 
meaning of the dying kanes final word rosebud for those who 
never saw the movie rosebud was the name of his sled 
hearst was the main source for citizen kane but welles also 
drew upon the lives of obert mccormick a wealthy chicago 
businessman who had himself tried to promote an untalented opera 
singer and samuel infull who had built an opera house in chicago 
instead of a straightforward narrative citizen kane jumps 
back and forth in time as the reporter interviews people who knew 
kane and newsreels depict the highlights of his public life it is 
similar in structure to marching song a play welles wrote when 
he was 17 based on a reporters search for the abolitionist john 
brown 
orson was fascinated by a story within a story said leaming 
a professor of theater and film at hunter college citizen kane 
was a logical development 
