<TEXT>
it appears that george bush wont give up on his 
idea of cutting the capital gains tax which pretty much guarantees 
an explosive battle in congress 
that battle will erupt because capital gains are seen as 
something that involve the rich but either that notion is false or 
millions of americans now qualify as rich and the list grows larger 
with every year 
in truth capital gains concern anyone who inherited or purchased 
a few shares of stock or a house or who in almost any other way 
built a financial estate through ingenuity hard work or just luck 
under the 1986 tax act the capital gains tax was raised from a 
maximum of 20 percent to 28 percent for all earners of capital 
gains the increase was 40 percent for wealthy taxpayers but 100 
percent for many poorer taxpayers who real capital gains rate was 
only 14 percent or 15 percent 
it brought capital gains taxes in line with taxes on ordinary 
income 
that was bad enough said critics who also observed other quirks 
in the situation that such taxes can be applied to income never 
made to buying power that never existed and to funds a taxpayer 
never got a chance to use 
definition capital gains are profits realized from the sale of 
capital assets such as securities or real estate 
often they involve risk and usually they are the results of 
longterm investments for this and other reasons including the 
nations need for such capital investments gains generally were 
taxed at less than ordinary income 
consider the consequences now of taxing such longterm gains at 
the same rate as ordinary income income that is taxed during the 
same year in which it is earned 
assume an investment of 5000 in stock held for seven years if 
the appreciation averages 10 percent over that time the investor 
will have about doubled his money the capital gains would be 
5000 the tax about 1400 
while it appears the invester earned 10 percent he really earned 
only 6 percent because the value of the dollar changed in that time 
inflation eroded it at a rate of 4 percent a year an assumption but 
a very safe one 
at 6 percent a year money will not double in seven years the 
5000 sum will grow to about 7100 in buying power but the 
investor will pay capital gains taxes as if it had grown to 10000 
he will pay 1400 in taxes 
deducting the taxes from the inflationadjusted total earned 
leaves him with just 5600 or 5700 an average annual gain of 
100 or less for having risked his money and invested his savings in 
the american economy 
the example is a modest one consider for example a person who 
put some money away back in 1970 with the idea of using it for 
retirement the investment has since tripled in value to a very tidy 
sum or has it 
consumer price inflation in 1970 was 59 percent followed by 43 
percent in 1971 33 percent in 1972 not too bad but then it hit 
62 percent in 1973 and 11 percent in 1974 it never fell below 58 
percent through 1978 
thereafter the tale becomes grim three successive years of 
doubledigit inflation hit the worst of these years being 1980 
when official consumer price inflation measured year to year struck 
135 percent 
by the year 1983 the value of the 1970 dollar had been cut in 
half and of course it has been cut additionally since then even 
though inflation has been restrained to an acceptable 3 to 5 
percent a year 
the 1970 investor has allegedly tripled his money assuming an 
investment of 5000 he now has more than 15000 although 
sensible people know that in 1970 dollars it is worth less than half 
that or about 7000 
nevertheless should that investor sell he has a 10000 capital 
gain on which taxes must be paid and that tax will levied at the 
same rate at which money currently earned is taxed that is as if 
it had current buying power 
in short the investor will be liable for 2800 tax on what in 
effect is 7000 in terms of the 1970 dollar he ends up with a net 
loss 
</TEXT>
