an international trade panel has 
recommended the united states amend its tariff act of 1930 to make 
it comply with international trade rules the eec commission said 
tuesday 
it said a disputes panel of the general agreement on tariffs and 
trade the world trade body found section 337 of the act violates 
international trade rules 
the section deals with the right of the us international trade 
commission to rule on patent violations by importers 
the disputes panel said by comparison patent violations of 
usproduced goods go to federal court where accused parties have a 
better chance to defend themselves than those before the itc 
the panels finding will be discussed by the full gatt council on 
feb 8 eec commission spokesman nico wegter said 
the commission is of course pleased with the fact that the 
panel shares the view of the commission that the united states 
violates international trade rules 
officials at the us mission to the eec declined to comment on 
the ruling that was issued in december but was not made public 
unitil tuesday 
the panels ruling stems from a 10yearold dispute between akzo 
nv the dutch chemicals group and du pont co of the united states 
over patent rights for aramid fibers these synthetic fibers are 
used in the automotive aerospace defence and construction 
industries 
in november 1985 the itc blocked imports into the united states 
of akzos aramid fibers saying the company had violated du ponts 
patent rights 
akzo complained to the eec commission about the procedure used by 
du pont to seek protection from foreign competitors under section 
337 of the tariffs act 
in 1987 the commission found the us law to amount to an unfair 
trade practice it took the issue to gatt where a special disputes 
panel was formed later that year 
the commission said tuesday if the gatt council which is made up 
of officials of the 100 or so gatt member states adopts the panels 
report the united states must take the necessary measures to 
rectify as quickly as possible the present situation 
a spokesman for the ec chemical federation cefic said akzo and 
du pont had settled their dispute while the investigation was 
continuing 
he welcomed the ruling on section 337 saying it represented was 
increasingly burdensome for eec businesses and said the panels 
ruling was a victory for the eec 
