<TEXT>
du pont co has received a patent on a 
compound blend that could accelerate the replacement of halogenated 
chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs which damage the earths ozone layer 
a spokesman said tuesday 
the company said the threecomponent blends of environmentally 
acceptable compounds will have no adverse effects on the 
environment compared to cfc12 one of the products suspected of 
depleting the ozone layer 
du pont is the largest maker of cfcs in the world and has said it 
will cease making the chemicals by the end of the century 
scientists say cfcs have the potential to damage the environment 
including decreasing the ozone layer a shield that protects the 
earth from ultraviolet light 
under the montreal protocol treaty countries producing cfcs have 
agreed to reduce cfc production by 50 percent by 1998 the united 
states has signed the agreement 
the new blends could be used for existing mediumtemperature food 
display cases vending machines water coolers home refrigerators 
and freezers and automobile air conditioners all of which make up 
about 30 percent of the cfc market in the united states 
the new blends would gradually be placed in items that use cfcs 
as they wear out otherwise we would not be able to phase out 
production of cfcs until all the equipment was off the market 
said tony mccain du pont manager of the alternative development 
program 
we will still work to find an alternative for new equipment 
this would go in parallel with it he said 
we have received a patent on the technology which says the 
blend works but it will take a couple of years to test it in 
operating systems to define all the changes that might be required 
in a refrigerator or car and then we have to finish the process 
development mccain said 
the new technology was made public monday at a meeting of the 
american society of heating refrigeration and air conditioning 
engineers in chicago 
candidate components for the blends include hcfc22 hfc152a and 
hcfc124 
mccain said hcfc124 is a new product 
mix those three together and you get something very close to 
what we had with cfc12 as far as performance he said 
mccain said the blends were more energy efficient than hfc134a 
the leading singleproduct candidate alternative for cfcs 
du pont plans to introduce a series of alternative products in a 
three to fiveyear period beginning in 1990 complete phaseout of 
cfcs may take until the turn of the century the company said 
</TEXT>
