<DOCNO> AP890131-0301 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal aviation officials ordered airlines 
tuesday to inspect all of four types of boeing airliners built in 
the last eight years after wiring mixups were found on four more 
planes 
in its most farreaching order to date on the possibility of 
crosswiring and crossplumbing in airline safety systems the 
federal aviation administration gave airlines 25 days to complete 
the testing of both engine and cargo hold safety systems in 741 
aircraft 
this will easily affect most airlines said faa spokesman 
fred farrar the inspections were ordered for 472 boeing 737s 33 
jumbo 747s 123 757s and 113 767s manufactured after dec 31 1980 
previous faa orders prompted by the discovery of fouledup wiring 
or plumbing in several boeing aircraft throughout the world were 
limited only to plumbing and wiring on individual types of airliners 
wiring and plumbing problems became the subject of faa orders 
after british authorities speculated the pilot of a british midland 
airways 737 was deceived into shutting down his only good engine in 
a crash that killed 44 people in england jan 8 
authorities have not concluded what caused both engines to be 
shut down in the british plane but since the crash crosswiring of 
engine or cargo hold fire warning systems has been found in other 
planes 
inspections ordered earlier by british authorities covered airbus 
a320s as well as boeing 737s but faulty wiring has been found only 
in boeing aircraft all of which are built in seattle 
boeing spokesman david jiminez said the aircraft builder had no 
immediate comment on the latest order officials of boeing and 
several airlines had said they agreed with previous orders as 
prudent measures to ensure safety 
the newly ordered tests are not expected to disrupt airline 
schedules and can be completed anytime over the next 3 weeks while 
the airliners are undergoing routine maintenance 
under the airworthiness directive issued by the faas seattle 
office airlines are ordered to repair and report any defects to the 
faa 
farrar said the four additional problems were found either during 
work done under previous directives or in independent testing by 
airlines 
they included faulty wiring on three 757s he said including one 
case of an incomplete circuit that would have kept a fire 
extinguisher from operating and two cases of crosswiring one would 
have indicated the wrong engine was overheating and the other would 
have set off the fire extinguisher to the wrong engine farrar said 
the fourth case involved crosswiring that would have indicated 
fire in the wrong engine of a 737 he said 
farrar said that while foreign airlines flying boeing aircraft 
are not required to follow the directives most of them will conduct 
the tests 
</TEXT>
