a california computer company has agreed to pay 
74 million to settle claims that one of its subsidiaries 
improperly charged the pentagon on contracts the justice department 
said tuesday 
the department said it had reached the agreement with computer 
and communications technology corp of san diego and the subsidiary 
zeta laboratories inc of san jose to settle a government claim 
that the defense department was defrauded on contract charges 
between 1983 and 1986 
the alleged improprieties were discovered in june 1986 when 
whittaker corp acquired zeta from cct the department said 
whittaker canceled the deal to acquire zeta which manufactures 
microwave components and subassemblies for weapons systems 
last october raymond yc ho the former president of zeta and 
william e fogarty the companys former chief financial officer 
pleaded guilty to criminal charges in connection with the case 
both men were fined and ordered to perform 1000 hours of 
community service 
the companies agreed to pay 1 million plus interest in four 
installments and remit the balance after cct sells the zeta 
subsidiary the department said the company could owe a total of 
750000 worth of interest depending upon when the final payment is 
made the department said 
